        "text_path": "sources/nag_hammadi/raw/thunder_perfect_mind/othergospels_thunder_primary.txt",
        "preview": "The Thunder, Perfect Mind\n\nIntroduction\n**1.** I was sent forth from [the] Power,\n\tand have come to those who meditate on me,\n\tand have been found among those who seek for me.\n**2.** Look at me, you who meditate on me,\n\tand you obedient ones, {obey me:1}.\n**3.** You who {expectantly wait:2} for me, embrace me,\n\tand send me not away from your sight,\n\tand make not your voice hateful to me, nor your hearing.\n**4.** Be not ignorant of me in any place or at any time.\n**5.** Be on your guard; be not ignorant of me\n\nFootnotes:\n[1] Literally, “you hearing ones . . . hear me.”\nLike the Biblical “hear/hearken,” the sense is “obey.”\n[2] The Coptic, like its Biblical cognates, can mean both “wait” and “expect.”\nI have combined both meanings.\n[3] This right-side popup shouldn't overflow the right, despite how far we are over\n\nFirst “I Am” Speech\n**1.** For I am the first and the last.\n**2.** I am the honored and the scorned.\n**3.** I am the whore and the holy.\n**4.** I am the wife and the virgin.\n**5.** I am [{the mother:1}] and the daughter.\n**6.** I am the limbs of my mother.\n\tI am the barren one whose children are many.\n**7.** I am she whose wedding is great,\n\tand I have taken no husband.\n**",
